§3 LIVY AS WRITER AND STYLIST.

Just as Livy’s life was passed under both the old and the new forms of government, the Republic and the Empire, so his language may be said to hover between two styles of Latinity. lt occupies a middle position between the golden Latin of Cicero and Caesar and the silver Latin of Tacitus and the Younger Pliny. Livy's Latin does not indeed diverge to a very great extent from that of Cicero 3 but the lapse from the latter’s high ideal of purity ,comes out every now and again in a certain freedom of construction which prose writers had not before permitted themselves, in the use of new words, in the adoption of poetical turns of expression, from all which it can be seen that Livy is leading the way to what is known as silver Latinity.
